            <!-- Event 11 -->
            <div class="timeline-event">
                <div class="event-date">1989 CE</div>
                <div class="event-content economic">
                    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Tokyo_stock_exchange_1989.jpg/800px-Tokyo_stock_exchange_1989.jpg" alt="Tokyo Stock Exchange 1989" class="event-image">
                    <div class="event-header">
                        <span class="event-icon">üíº</span>
                        <h3 class="event-title">Heisei Period & Bubble Economy Peak</h3>
                    </div>
                    <p class="event-description">Emperor Akihito's ascension marked the beginning of the Heisei period. The late 1980s saw Japan's asset price bubble peak, with Tokyo's real estate values exceeding the entire United States. The bubble burst in 1991, leading to the "Lost Decades" of economic stagnation.</p>
                    <div class="significance">
                        <h4>Historical Significance</h4>
                        <p>The bubble era demonstrated both the success of Japan's post-war developmental state and its vulnerabilities, forcing structural reforms and highlighting the limits of centralized economic planning.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Event 12 -->
            <div class="timeline-event">
                <div class="event-date">2011 CE</div>
                <div class="event-content political">
                    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/2011_Tohoku_earthquake_tsunami_01.jpg/800px-2011_Tohoku_earthquake_tsunami_01.jpg" alt="2011 T≈çhoku earthquake destruction" class="event-image">
                    <div class="event-header">
                        <span class="event-icon">üåä</span>
                        <h3 class="event-title">T≈çhoku Earthquake & Fukushima Disaster</h3>
                    </div>
                    <p class="event-description">A magnitude 9.0 earthquake triggered a massive tsunami that killed over 18,000 people and caused the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear meltdown‚Äîthe worst nuclear disaster since Chernobyl.</p>
                    <div class="significance">
                        <h4>Historical Significance</h4>
                        <p>The disaster revealed strengths in Japanese social cohesion but also exposed systemic weaknesses in regulatory oversight, accelerating the shift away from nuclear power.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
